"Wagner D.","Assessment of the probability of extreme weather events and their potential effects in large conurbations",1999,"Atmospheric Environment","33","24-25",,"4151","4155",,,10.1016/S1352-2310(99)00157-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033035916&partnerID=40&md5=fab9ca09aaacdfdfe633e6e88c53e10e","Schönbergstrasse 18, D-79189 Bad Krozingen, Germany","Wagner, D., Schönbergstrasse 18, D-79189 Bad Krozingen, Germany","The likelihood of occurrence of extreme high-temperature run events is estimated for different values of the event intensity and persistence from very long synthetic time series of daily maximum temperatures generated by Monte Carlo simulations using a first-order autoregressive or Markov model. A theoretical analysis reveals a higher relative sensitivity of the simulated extreme event probabilities to changes in the variability of climate than to changes in its mean state. Moreover, this sensitivity relatively increases at a nonlinear rate the more extreme the event. The developed probabilistic model is applied in order to derive local scenarios of extreme high-temperature run events for a large conurbation like the city of Berlin assuming both arbitrary hypothetical and physically based new climate states described by changes in the model parameters (e.g. the mean, the standard deviation and the first-order autocorrelation of the daily maximum temperature time series). As a consequence of a 1.7°C increase in the mean as well as a 19% increase in the temperature variability in July as predicted by the climate model ECHAM-1/LSG assuming an unrestricted future increase in the global atmospheric concentration of climate relevant greenhouse gases according to the IPCC Scenario A ('Business as usual') the intensity as well as the persistence of extreme high-temperature run events will rise considerably up to the end of the next century. In particular, intense hot spells characterized by at least five consecutive daily maximum temperatures equaling or exceeding 33°C are expected to occur every eight years under the new climate conditions compared to a current repetition time of about 47 years. The potential environmental e!ects might be a significant increase in the heat-stress-related morbidity and mortality rate, an aggravation of the summer smog situation and a destabilization of the urban ecosystems. (C) 1999 Elsevier Science Ltd. All rights reserved.The likelihood of occurrence of extreme high-temperature run events is estimated for different values of the event of intensity and persistence from very long synthetic time series of daily maximum temperatures generated by Monte Carlo simulations using a first-order autoregressive or Markov model. A theoretical analysis reveals a higher relative sensitivity of the simulated extreme event probabilities to changes in the variability of climate than to changes in its mean state. Moreover, this sensitivity relatively increases at a nonlinear rate the more extreme the event. The developed probabilistic model is applied in order to derive local scenarios of extreme high-temperature run events for a large conurbation like the city of Berlin assuming both arbitrary hypothetical and physically based new climate states described by changes in the model parameters (e.g. the mean, the standard deviation and the first-order autocorrelation of the daily maximum temperature time series). As a consequence of a 1.7 °C increase in the mean as well as a 19% increase in the temperature variability in July as predicted by the climate model ECHAM_1/LSG assuming an unrestricted future increase in the global atmospheric concentration of climate relevant greenhouse gases according to the IPCC Scenario A (`Business as usual') the intensity as well as the persistence of extreme high-temperature run events will rise considerably up to the end of the next century. In particular, intense hot spells characterized by at least five consecutive daily maximum temperatures equaling or exceeding 33 °C are expected to occur every eight years under the new climate conditions compared to a current repetition time of about 47 years. The potential environmental effects might be a significant increase in the heat-stress-related morbidity and mortality rate, an aggravation of the summer smog situation and a destabilization of the urban ecosystems.","Climate scenarios; Global warming; Impact assessment; Probabilistic model; Weather extremes","Air pollution; Climate change; Computer simulation; Correlation methods; Ecosystems; Environmental impact; Markov processes; Mathematical models; Monte Carlo methods; Probability; Regression analysis; Time series analysis; Autoregressive analysis; Morbidity rate; Mortality rate; Weather forecasting; climate modeling; extreme event; prediction; weather forecasting; conference paper; environmental impact assessment; environmental temperature; Germany; greenhouse effect; high temperature; model; priority journal; probability; simulation; system analysis; weather",,,,,,"Cubasch, U., Hasselmann, K., Höck, H., Maier-Reimer, E., Mikolajewicz, U., Santer, B., Sausen, R., Time-dependent greenhouse warming computations with a coupled ocean-atmosphere model (1992) Climate Dynamics, 8, pp. 55-69; Houghton, J.T., Scientific assessment of climate change; Survey of the IPCC Working Group I Report (1991) Climate Change, Science, Impacts and Policy, pp. 243-246. , WMO; Kalkstein, L.S., Maunder, W.J., Jendritzky, G., (1996) Climate and Human Health, Second Ed., , WMO-Nr.843, Geneva, WMO; Katz, R.W., Brown, B.G., Extreme events in a changing climate: Variability is more important than averages (1992) Climatic Change, 21, pp. 289-302; Mearns, L.O., Katz, R.W., Schneider, S.H., Extreme high-temperature events: Changes in their probabilities with changes in mean temperature (1984) Journal of Climatology and Applied Meteorology, 23, pp. 1601-1613; Oke, T.R., The energetic basis of the urban heat island (1982) Quarterly Journal of Royal Meteorological Society, 108, pp. 1-24; Wagner, D., Hupfer, P., Schmidt, T., On the assessment of regional climate change effects in large urban areas (1993) Proceedings of the 13th International Congress of Biometeorology, 3 (2 PART), pp. 813-818. , In: Maarouf, A.R., Barthakur, N.N., Haufe, W.O. (Eds.), September 12-18, 1993. Calgary, Alberta, Canada; Wagner, D., Scenarios of extreme temperature events (1996) Climatic Change, 33, pp. 385-407","Wagner, D.Schonbergstrasse 18, D-79189 Bad Krozingen, Germany",,"","Elsevier Science Ltd, Exeter","Proceedings of the 1996 International Conference on Urban Climatology (ICUC'96)","10 June 1996 through 14 June 1996","Essen, Ger",55617,13522310,,AENVE,,"English","Atmos. Environ.",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-0033035916
